tConclusion -- tAppendix A -- tAppendix B -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA number of reports in the US have highlighted the country’s need for improved second language skills for both national security and economic competitiveness. The Language Flagship program, launched in 2002, aims to raise expectations regarding language proficiency levels at the post-secondary level and to address structural gaps in the curricula of many L2 programs. This federally funded program provides opportunities for US undergraduate students in any specialization to reach a professional level of competence in a targeted second language by graduation. This volume highlights innovative practices that enable students to achieve this goal – even those with no exposure to the second language prior to university. This book explores the rationale and history of the federal program and showcases models and strategies of existing Flagship programs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCommunicative competencezUnited States. 0aLanguage and languagesxStudy and teachingzUnited States. 0aSecond language acquisition. 7aEDUCATION / Educational Policy & Reform / General.2bisacsh  aAdvanced-Superior language learning.  aEducation policy.  aIntercultural competence.  aLanguage Flagship.  aLanguage acquisition.  aLanguage learning.  aLanguage teaching.  aPostsecondary foreign language education in the United States.  aProficiency-oriented instruction.  aUS.1 aAl-Batal, Mahmoud, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlsufieva, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlves, Viviane Klen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnishchenkova, Valerie, econt